    <div id="interview" class="tab-content active">
        <div class="section">
            <h2>📋 Pharmacovigilance Interview Questions</h2>

            <h3>Basic Concepts & Definitions</h3>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q1: What is pharmacovigilance? Define it and explain its importance.</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong> Pharmacovigilance is the science and activities relating to the detection, assessment, understanding, and prevention of adverse effects of medicinal products. It involves:
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
                        <li><strong>Detection:</strong> Identifying adverse drug reactions (ADRs) through post-marketing surveillance</li>
                        <li><strong>Assessment:</strong> Evaluating causality, severity, and risk-benefit profile</li>
                        <li><strong>Prevention:</strong> Taking action to minimize patient harm</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Importance:</strong> Ensures drug safety post-launch, protects public health, maintains drug efficacy-safety balance, and supports regulatory compliance.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q2: What is the difference between pharmacovigilance and drug safety monitoring?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
                        <li><strong>Pharmacovigilance:</strong> Broader term covering detection, assessment, understanding, and prevention of ADRs. It's a proactive science.</li>
                        <li><strong>Drug Safety Monitoring:</strong> Narrower subset focused on continuous monitoring of drug safety. It's more reactive.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;">Pharmacovigilance encompasses drug safety monitoring as well as signal detection, risk management, and public communication.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q3: What is an Adverse Drug Reaction (ADR)? Classify them.</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong> <strong>ADR Definition:</strong> Any response to a drug that is noxious and unintended, occurring at doses normally used for diagnosis, therapy, or prophylaxis.
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>WHO Classification (Type A–E):</strong></p>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px;">
                        <li><strong>Type A (Augmented):</strong> Dose-dependent, predictable (e.g., anticholinergic effects)</li>
                        <li><strong>Type B (Bizarre):</strong> Dose-independent, unpredictable (e.g., drug allergies)</li>
                        <li><strong>Type C (Chronic):</strong> Occur after prolonged exposure (e.g., organ toxicity)</li>
                        <li><strong>Type D (Delayed):</strong> Appear after a delay (e.g., teratogenicity)</li>
                        <li><strong>Type E (End-of-dose):</strong> Related to drug withdrawal (e.g., rebound hypertension)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Causality Assessment</h3>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q4: What is causality assessment? Name and explain the major scales used.</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong> Causality assessment determines the probability that an observed ADR was caused by the suspect drug.
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Major Scales:</strong></p>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px;">
                        <li><strong>Naranjo Scale:</strong> 10-question algorithm; most widely used. Score: Definite (≥9), Probable (5–8), Possible (1–4), Unlikely (≤0).</li>
                        <li><strong>WHO-UMC Scale:</strong> 6 categories: Certain, Probable/Likely, Possible, Unlikely, Unrelated, Unassessable.</li>
                        <li><strong>Karch & Lasagna Scale:</strong> 7-point scale considering temporal relationship, dose-response, alternative causes.</li>
                        <li><strong>Jones Scale:</strong> Used for liver injury; 14-point scoring system.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q5: Explain temporal relationship and dechallenge/rechallenge concepts.</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong>
                    <p><strong>Temporal Relationship:</strong> The interval between drug administration and ADR occurrence. Shorter intervals strengthen causality (within expected pharmacokinetic window).</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Dechallenge:</strong> Discontinuation of the suspected drug and observation of ADR resolution. Positive dechallenge (ADR improves) strengthens causality.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Rechallenge:</strong> Re-administration of the drug to reproduce the ADR. Positive rechallenge (ADR reoccurs) strongly supports causality but is rarely done due to ethical concerns.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Regulatory & Reporting Aspects</h3>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q6: What are MedDRA and PharmacoVigilance System (PhVS)?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong>
                    <p><strong>MedDRA (Medical Dictionary for Regulatory Activities):</strong> Standardized, hierarchical medical terminology used globally for coding adverse events in pharmacovigilance. Uses five levels: System Organ Classes (SOC), High-Level Group Terms (HLGT), High-Level Terms (HLT), Preferred Terms (PT), and Lower-Level Terms (LLT).</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>PhVS:</strong> System of activities and tools to monitor drug safety post-marketing. Includes adverse event databases, signal detection, periodic safety updates.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q7: What is the NDA/IND and post-marketing surveillance obligations?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong>
                    <p><strong>NDA (New Drug Application):</strong> Regulatory submission containing clinical data; if approved, drug enters market.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>IND (Investigational New Drug):</strong> Preclinical/clinical development status before NDA.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Post-Marketing Obligations:</strong></p>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px;">
                        <li>Periodic Safety Update Reports (PSUR) every 6 months–annually</li>
                        <li>Signal detection and risk-benefit reassessment</li>
                        <li>Risk Minimization Strategies (RMS)</li>
                        <li>Updates to label/SmPC based on safety data</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q8: What is a Safety Update, PERIODIC SAFETY UPDATE REPORT (PSUR), and Development Safety Update Report (DSUR)?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong>
                    <p><strong>PSUR:</strong> Comprehensive periodic report submitted post-approval detailing all adverse events, signals, and safety updates. Frequency depends on regulatory requirements.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>DSUR:</strong> Submitted during clinical development phases; similar to PSUR but for investigational drugs.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Safety Update:</strong> Ad-hoc communication of urgent safety information (e.g., black box warning, label change).</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Signal Detection & Risk Management</h3>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q9: Define signal detection. What are the methods and tools used?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong> <strong>Signal:</strong> Information on a possible causal relationship between an adverse event and a medicinal product that is worthy of further investigation.
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Methods:</strong></p>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px;">
                        <li><strong>Spontaneous Reporting Analysis:</strong> Review of adverse event reports (e.g., FAERS, VigiBase)</li>
                        <li><strong>Disproportionality Analysis:</strong> Statistical comparison (ROR, PRR, IC)</li>
                        <li><strong>Epidemiological Studies:</strong> Case-control, cohort studies</li>
                        <li><strong>Data Mining:</strong> Machine learning on large databases</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Tools:</strong> VigiBase, FAERS, EudraVigilance, PharmGKB, SAS, SPSS.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q10: What is risk-benefit assessment? Explain Risk Minimization Strategies (RMS).</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong> <strong>Risk-Benefit Assessment:</strong> Systematic evaluation of the benefits vs. risks of a drug post-marketing, considering efficacy, safety profile, patient population, and alternatives.
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Risk Minimization Strategies:</strong> Proactive measures to reduce ADR occurrence:</p>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px;">
                        <li><strong>Routine RMS:</strong> Labeling updates, dosage adjustment, contraindications</li>
                        <li><strong>Additional RMS:</strong> Risk Evaluation and Mitigation Strategies (REMS), restricted distribution programs, patient education, monitoring programs</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Clinical Scenarios & Problem-Solving</h3>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q11: A patient on metformin develops lactic acidosis. How would you assess causality using Naranjo?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong> Using the 10-item Naranjo Scale:
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
                        <li>Are there previous conclusive reports on this reaction? (+1)</li>
                        <li>Did the adverse event appear after the suspected drug was given? (+2)</li>
                        <li>Did the adverse reaction improve when the drug was discontinued? (+1)</li>
                        <li>Did the adverse reaction reappear when the drug was readministered? (+2 if yes)</li>
                        <li>Are there alternative causes? Consider renal impairment, dehydration (−1 if alternative exists)</li>
                        <li>Temporal relationship within known pharmacokinetics? (+1)</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Expected Score:</strong> 8–10 (Probable to Definite) given known risk with renal impairment.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q12: What would you do if you identified a potential new safety signal in a drug?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong>
                    <ol style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
                        <li><strong>Data Collection:</strong> Gather all relevant reports and literature data</li>
                        <li><strong>Causality Assessment:</strong> Evaluate using Naranjo or WHO-UMC</li>
                        <li><strong>Frequency Analysis:</strong> Check disproportionality (ROR, PRR, IC values)</li>
                        <li><strong>Severity & Outcome:</strong> Assess if serious, hospitalization-related, fatal</li>
                        <li><strong>Escalation:</strong> Notify medical, regulatory, and quality teams</li>
                        <li><strong>Action Plan:</strong> Consider label update, healthcare professional communication, or RMS</li>
                        <li><strong>Documentation:</strong> Maintain complete audit trail</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>India-Specific Regulations</h3>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q13: What are India's pharmacovigilance regulations (GVKS, PvPI)?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong>
                    <p><strong>GVKS (Grievances Vigilance Knowledge System):</strong> India's national pharmacovigilance portal managed by CDSCO. Healthcare professionals and patients can report ADRs.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>PvPI (Pharmacovigilance Programme of India):</strong> Established by CDSCO; hospitals and institutions participate and submit reports.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Key Requirements:</strong></p>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px;">
                        <li>Mandatory reporting of serious ADRs within 14–30 days</li>
                        <li>Follow ICH-GCP and WHO guidelines</li>
                        <li>Maintenance of adverse event databases</li>
                        <li>Coordination with international vigilance programs</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q14: What does CDSCO expect from pharmaceutical companies in India regarding pharmacovigilance?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px;">
                        <li><strong>Dedicated PV Department:</strong> With qualified safety pharmacist</li>
                        <li><strong>Case Tracking System:</strong> Documented receipt, assessment, and follow-up of ADRs</li>
                        <li><strong>PSUR/DSUR Submission:</strong> As per schedule</li>
                        <li><strong>Signal Detection:</strong> Proactive monitoring of safety databases</li>
                        <li><strong>Risk Minimization:</strong> Implement RMS as needed</li>
                        <li><strong>GVKS Reporting:</strong> Report serious ADRs to national portal</li>
                        <li><strong>Product Quality:</strong> Ensure no post-market quality issues</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Advanced Topics</h3>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q15: Explain the concept of Risk Evaluation and Mitigation Strategies (REMS) with an example.</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong> <strong>REMS:</strong> A regulatory program ensuring benefits of a drug outweigh its risks. Components:
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
                        <li><strong>Communication Plan:</strong> Healthcare professional and patient education</li>
                        <li><strong>Elements to Assure Safe Use (ETASU):</strong> Restricted distribution, prescriber/patient enrollment, dispensing restrictions</li>
                        <li><strong>Implementation System:</strong> Monitoring and evaluation</li>
                        <li><strong>Timetable for Assessment:</strong> Regular evaluation of effectiveness</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Example:</strong> Thalidomide REMS in the US—restricted to certified prescribers, pharmacies, and patients due to teratogenicity risk.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q16: What is pharmacokinetic-pharmacodynamic (PK-PD) relationship in adverse effects?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong>
                    <p><strong>PK-PD Relationship:</strong> Understanding how drug concentration relates to adverse effects helps predict risk and implement preventive measures.</p>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
                        <li><strong>Relationship to PK:</strong> High plasma levels → increased ADR risk (e.g., digitalis toxicity)</li>
                        <li><strong>Relationship to PD:</strong> Receptor saturation or enzyme inhibition → prolonged effect or toxicity</li>
                        <li><strong>Therapeutic Drug Monitoring (TDM):</strong> Maintains levels within therapeutic window to minimize ADRs</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q17: How do you differentiate between drug-drug interactions and pharmacovigilance concerns?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong>
                    <p><strong>Drug-Drug Interactions (DDI):</strong> Physical or chemical interactions between two drugs affecting absorption, distribution, metabolism, or elimination.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Pharmacovigilance Concern:</strong> Unexpected, serious, or novel ADRs attributed to a single drug or combination.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Overlap:</strong> DDI can manifest as an ADR requiring PV investigation. Both require monitoring and appropriate communication.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q18: What is a "cluster" in pharmacovigilance? How is it detected?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong> <strong>Cluster:</strong> An unusual increase in the frequency of a specific ADR within a defined time period or geographic area.
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Detection:</strong></p>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px;">
                        <li>Spontaneous reporting review (temporal or geographic grouping)</li>
                        <li>Statistical analysis: Chi-square test, temporal trend analysis</li>
                        <li>Comparison with historical baseline rates</li>
                        <li>Investigation of common factors (batch/lot, production, storage conditions)</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Example:</strong> Sudden increase in liver toxicity cases of a drug in a specific region → investigate product quality or counterfeit drugs.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Data Management & Tools</h3>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q19: What is VigiBase? How is it used in pharmacovigilance?</strong>
                <div class="answer-box">
                    <strong>Answer:</strong> <strong>VigiBase:</strong> WHO's global database of individual case safety reports (ICSRs). Contains millions of adverse event reports from >130 countries.
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Uses:</strong></p>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px;">
                        <li>Signal detection and validation</li>
                        <li>Post-marketing surveillance trends</li>
                        <li>International comparison of safety data</li>
                        <li>Pharmacovigilance research</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Access:</strong> Through WHO Collaborating Centre; provides reports and statistical outputs (ROR, IC values).</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="question-box" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
                <strong>Q20: Compare FAERS, EudraVigilance, and VigiBase.</strong>
